---
import Layout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Impact Score Methodology - SurviveTheAI"
  description="How SurviveTheAI assigns Impact Scores and how readers should interpret the number."
>
  <main class="bg-white py-14 text-neutral-900 sm:py-16">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-screen-xl space-y-10 px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <header class="space-y-3">
        <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-neutral-500">Methodology</p>
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-neutral-900 sm:text-4xl">Impact Score methodology</h1>
        <p class="max-w-3xl text-lg text-neutral-700 sm:text-xl">
          Impact Score is STA&apos;s editorial shorthand for how disruptive, near-term, and household-relevant a story appears right now.
          It is not a prediction market, not a probability claim, and not a moral ranking.
        </p>
      </header>

      <section class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-3">
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6 shadow-sm">
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-neutral-500">What it is for</p>
          <h2 class="text-xl font-black text-neutral-900">Reader triage</h2>
          <p class="mt-3 text-neutral-700">
            The score helps readers sort the library faster by signaling which pieces describe larger, faster, or harder-to-ignore pressure.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6 shadow-sm">
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-neutral-500">What it is not</p>
          <h2 class="text-xl font-black text-neutral-900">Not a certainty score</h2>
          <p class="mt-3 text-neutral-700">
            A higher score does not mean the article is "more true." Truth is handled through sourcing, Claims &amp; Verification, and corrections.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6 shadow-sm">
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-neutral-500">Why publish it</p>
          <h2 class="text-xl font-black text-neutral-900">Transparent editorial framing</h2>
          <p class="mt-3 text-neutral-700">
            The goal is to make the score legible enough that readers can understand the editorial logic behind the number instead of treating it as decoration.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="rounded-3xl border border-neutral-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm sm:p-8">
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-neutral-500">How STA scores</p>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-neutral-900 sm:text-3xl">Four editorial inputs</h2>
          <p class="max-w-4xl text-neutral-700">
            Editors assign the score by combining four practical lenses. The model is intentionally simple: it exists to guide reading priority, not to simulate scientific precision.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="mt-6 grid gap-5 lg:grid-cols-2">
          <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-5">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-black text-neutral-900">1. Household impact</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-neutral-700">
              How strongly the issue could affect a reader&apos;s work, family, attention, money, safety, or relationships if it materializes.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-5">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-black text-neutral-900">2. Time horizon</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-neutral-700">
              Whether the pressure looks immediate, already active, or likely to matter soon enough that waiting carries real cost.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-5">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-black text-neutral-900">3. Adaptation difficulty</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-neutral-700">
              How hard it is for ordinary people or institutions to respond once the pressure shows up. Higher difficulty pushes the score upward.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-5">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-black text-neutral-900">4. Spillover breadth</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-neutral-700">
              Whether the issue stays narrow or cascades across multiple parts of life, sectors, or trust systems at once.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-[minmax(0,1.15fr)_minmax(320px,0.85fr)]">
        <div class="rounded-3xl border border-neutral-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm sm:p-8">
          <div class="space-y-3">
            <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-neutral-500">How to read the number</p>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-neutral-900 sm:text-3xl">Interpretation bands</h2>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-6 space-y-4">
            <div class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-5">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-black text-neutral-900">40-59: meaningful, but narrower</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-neutral-700">
                Important issue, but either the scope is narrower, the timeline is slower, or the adaptation path is more manageable.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-5">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-black text-neutral-900">60-74: high attention</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-neutral-700">
                Readers should treat this as a real pressure point with practical consequences, not background noise.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-5">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-black text-neutral-900">75+: urgent and broadly consequential</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-neutral-700">
                These stories combine high household stakes, difficult adaptation, and enough breadth or speed that delay becomes expensive.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-3xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6 shadow-sm sm:p-8">
          <div class="space-y-3">
            <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-neutral-500">Guardrails</p>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-neutral-900 sm:text-3xl">How STA keeps the score honest</h2>
          </div>
          <ul class="mt-6 space-y-3 text-neutral-700">
            <li>The score is editorial judgment, not a hidden algorithm.</li>
            <li>It does not replace sourcing, claims review, or uncertainty labeling.</li>
            <li>Scores can change when facts, timelines, or adaptation assumptions change.</li>
            <li>Lower scores are still important; they usually reflect narrower scope or slower timing, not dismissal.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="rounded-3xl border border-neutral-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm sm:p-8">
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-neutral-500">Bottom line</p>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-neutral-900 sm:text-3xl">Impact Score tells you where to look first</h2>
          <p class="max-w-4xl text-neutral-700">
            Use the score as one reading aid: start with the highest-pressure items, then use the article itself, Claims &amp; Verification,
            and your own context to decide what matters most for you.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>
